#installoperatingsystem

May 3, 2026

With the physical hardware diagnosed and the network foundation set, it is time to actually bring the machine to life. This log covers the step-by-step fundamentals 
of Operating System installation and initial configuration.

MEDIA PREPARATION
  INSTALLATION MEDIA: A USB is typically just a storage device. However, by altering it's MBR (Master Boot Record) or GUID Partition Table (GPT) you can actually turn it into a 
  bootable hard drive. Tools like the Media Control Tool (MCT) will do this automatically. A tool like Rufus will allow you to customize the settings.

  ARCHITECTURE: This is referring to the instruction set of the CPU. x64 being the the 64-bit standard for Intel and AMD processors found in most desktops. ARM (Advanced RISC Machine)
  is used for high-efficiency chips (like the Snapdragon in some laptops or Apple’s M-series). You cannot run x64 Windows on an ARM chip without specific emulation, and vice versa.

  ISO: Think of an ISO as a "digital clone" of a physical DVD. It contains every file and the exact sector-by-sector layout of the installer.

  SPECS: Before starting, verify the hardware. Windows 11, for example, requires at least 4GB of RAM, 64GB of storage, and a compatible 1GHz 64-bit processor. If the hardware is 
  too old, the installer will throw a "This PC cannot run Windows" error.


BIOS/UEFI CONFIGURATION
  BOOT PRIORITY: By default, a PC looks at the internal SSD for an OS. To install a new one, you must interrupt the boot (usually by tapping F2, F12, or DEL) and move the USB Flash 
  Drive to the #1 spot in the Boot Order.

  UEFI vs. BIOS (LEGACY): BIOS is the old 1980s-era standard. UEFI is the modern replacement. UEFI allows for faster boot times, supports larger hard drives, and provides a graphical 
  mouse-driven interface. Most modern OSs require UEFI.

  SECURE BOOT: This is a feature of UEFI that ensures only software with a "digital signature" from a trusted provider (like Microsoft) can run at startup. It prevents rootkits (stealthy 
  malware) from hijacking the boot process before the antivirus even loads.

  TPM 2.0: Trusted Platform Module is a dedicated security chip (or firmware) on the motherboard that handles encryption keys. Windows 11 uses this to power features like BitLocker. 
  If TPM is disabled in BIOS, Windows 11 will refuse to install.


DISK MANAGEMENT/PARTITIONING
  FILE SYSTEMS (NTFS vs. FAT32): NTFS (New Technology File System) is the Windows standard because it supports massive file sizes and security permissions. FAT32 is an older format used 
  for USB sticks; it is highly compatible but cannot hold a single file larger than 4GB.  

  PARTITION TYPES (GPT vs. MBR): This is the "blueprint" for the drive. MBR is old and limited to 4 partitions and 2TB drives. GPT (GUID Partition Table) is the modern requirement for 
  UEFI and Windows 11, supporting nearly unlimited partitions and massive drive sizes.

  UNALLOCATED SPACE: This is a drive that has no partitions—no "Drive C:" or "Drive D:". In a "Clean Install," you delete all existing partitions until the drive is 100% Unallocated 
  Space, ensuring no old data or viruses interfere with the new OS.

  SYSTEM RESERVED PARTITIONS: When you install Windows, it creates tiny "hidden" slices (usually 100MB–500MB). One is the EFI System Partition (the "starter motor" for the OS) and the 
  other is the Recovery Environment. If you delete these, Windows will fail to boot.


POST-INSTALLATION: 
  DRIVERS: Even if Windows is running, the hardware might be "blind." A Driver is a translator. For example, without a Chipset Driver, the motherboard can't manage power correctly; 
  without a NIC Driver, you can't connect to the internet.

  UPDATES: The version of Windows on your USB is likely months old. Running Windows Update immediately is critical to patch "Zero Day" security vulnerabilities that have been 
  discovered since that installer was made.

  ACTIVATION: This connects your hardware to a license. In a home setting, this is a Product Key. In a corporate setting, this often happens automatically via a Digital License 
  tied to the motherboard's ID in the cloud.

  OOBE (OUT OF BOX EXPERIENCE): This is the "Hi there" blue screen phase. Here you set the Regional Settings (Time/Date), create the User Account, and choose Privacy Settings.


PXE (Preboot Execution Environment)- An industry standard client-server interface that allows a computer to boot and install an operating system over a network connection (Ethernet) 
without the need for physical media like a USB or hard drive.

SWAP- A dedicated space on the storage drive used as Virtual RAM. It prevents system failure during high memory usage and is required for hibernation. Traditionally, Swap is sized 
at 2x the amount of physical RAM, though on modern systems with 16GB+ of RAM, a smaller Swap (2GB–4GB) is usually sufficient.

SYSPREP- The main goal of Sysprep is to remove system-specific data from a Windows installation. This allows you to take a "snapshot" (Golden Image) of a configured PC and deploy it
to hundreds of other machines without errors.

FORMATTING- The process of initializing a partition with a specific File System (NTFS, FAT32, EXT4). It creates the internal structure (Master File Table) required for the OS to store 
and retrieve data. A "Quick Format" resets the file table, while a "Full Format" also checks the physical disk for errors.
